Addicted to hitpoints since July, 2000...</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/unocturnexev.showPublicProfile?language=EN>NocturneXev</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 10<br> <font color=#FF0000>(10/9/02 12:17:14 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2198.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Is it such a big deal?</span><hr size=1> A warrior can have 9375 hps and still get healed to full from one bubble of health with this new Complete Heal.  Not sure exactly what the uberest of warriors will have in PoP, but as far as I can tell it will mean very little to all but the very top level players.<br>
<br>
Speaking as a non-top-level player, I'm not dismayed.  If Uberguild01 decides to ditch their level 65, 11khp warrior for a level 65, 9.5khp shadowknight then I can understand their concern, but I think overall it'll just mean a variation of standard tactics (like having another healer dropping &quot;top-off&quot; heals onto the MA at regular intervals).<br>
<br>
Frankly, I don't really see the point of this change, although it may become much clearer once PoP arrives. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/ugalaian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>galaian</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 10<br> <font color=#FF0000>(10/9/02 12:46:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2198.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Is it such a big deal?</span><hr size=1> Good point here..  a 7500hp Cheal isn't the end of the world, and FAR from the end of the class.<br>
<br>
Let's say this mythical 11khp warrior exists.  If your cleric is on the ball, they start casting when you are close to 50% health.<br>
<br>
11,000/2=5,500<br>
<br>
This leaves a 2khp buffer.  On high-end encounters, there is always a cheal rotation going.  If everything is going well, I rarely see the MT drop below 40% health.  Let's wait and see what happens in the future before we declare warriors useless.<br>
